PROLOGUE

The prologues to the plays of Plautus are, ior the most part, spurious, having been composed at a time when the old plays were revived for the stage. The prologue to the Trinummas, however, is skillfully designed and may well be genuine. Itis the only one in which two speakers appear.

1. hac: titis way. -gnata=ncto; this archaia form is used even by virgil-munus iungaris: suaper always takes the ac- cusative in Plautus. So too abutor, but utor and fruor take the ab· lative; potior takes accusative, ablatlve, or genitive; vescor does not occur in Plautus.

2. finem: ie. of our Journey. - quem dicam: indirect question.
